                  <decoDesc resp="#PA">
                     <summary>
                        <ref target="https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000468709">Pächt and Alexander</ref> i. 445, pl. XXXVI
                     </summary>
                     <decoNote type="decInit">One fine initial</decoNote> 
                     <decoNote type="decInit">Many good initials</decoNote>
                  
                     <decoNote>
                        <p>
                     C. R. Dodwell, <title>
                              <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/434020/bodleian_library_western_medieval_manuscripts_bibliography/tags/MS.%20Bodl.%20701/items/VJ54MXHG/item-list"> 
                        The Canterbury School of Illumination, 1066-1200</ref>
                           </title> (Cambridge University Press, 1954), p. 117, identifies MS. Bodl. 707 as one of a group of Exeter manuscripts from the late eleventh and 
                     early twelfth centuries which are illuminated in the 'Carilef' style that is associated with the Norman books given to Durham by 
                     <persName key="person_159" role="fmo">William of St Carilef</persName>, e.g. 
                     the Carilef Bible (<ref target="https://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ark/32150_s11n79h433b.xml">Durham Cathedral Library, MS. A. II. 4</ref>). 
                     The other manuscripts from Dodwell's group are 
                     <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_1351">MS. Bodl. 301</ref>,  
                     <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_1768">MS. Bodl. 783</ref>, 
                     and <ref target="https://medieval.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/catalog/manuscript_1801">MS. Bodl. 813</ref>
                     [NB: Dodwell lists MS. Bodl. 701 but must have intended MS. Bodl. 707]</p>
                     </decoNote>
                     
                     <decoNote>Pächt and Alexander note similarities to Durham Cathedral Library, <ref target="https://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ark/32150_s1br86b3672.xml">
                        MS. B. III. 16</ref> 
                        <ref target="https://iiif.durham.ac.uk/index.html?manifest=t2mr781wg027">(digitised)</ref> and to related manuscripts from Jumièges, St. Ouen, Rouen, and Bayeux. Perhaps written by Normans in England</decoNote>
                     
                  </decoDesc>
                  
                  
